  "plain_language_summary": "Astronomers using NASA's James Webb Space Telescope have found evidence that TRAPPIST-1 b, an Earth-sized rocky planet orbiting a small red star, may have an atmosphere. By observing how the planet's brightness changes as it orbitsshowing different faces toward usthe team measured heat moving from its permanently sunlit side to its dark side. This heat movement suggests something is transporting energy around the planet, which a bare rock with no air could not do. They also detected a subtle dip in brightness near a wavelength where carbon dioxide absorbs light, matching what we would expect from an atmosphere. While these results argue against a completely airless surface, the exact composition and thickness of any atmosphere remains uncertain. Follow-up observations will be needed to confirm and characterize this potential atmosphere.",
